# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afghanistan-national-cricket-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The **1975 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '75**) was the inaugural men's Cricket World Cup, and the first major tournament in the history of One Day International (ODI) cricket.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference (ICC), it took place in England, between 7 June and 21 June 1975.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was sponsored by Prudential Assurance Company and had eight participating countries: the six Test-playing teams of the time – Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, the West Indies – and the two leading Associate nations at the time – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The teams were divided into two groups of four, with each team playing each other in their group once; the top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals, with the winners of these matches meeting in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match consisted of 60 overs per side and was played in traditional white clothing and with red balls; all were played and ended in daylight.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] England and New Zealand finished as the top two teams in Group A, while the West Indies finished top of the Group B table ahead of Australia as the four teams qualified through to the semi-finals.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia defeated England and the West Indies defeated New Zealand in the semi-finals, the West Indies which came into the tournament as favourites, defeated Australia in the final at Lord's by 17 runs to become the first World Cup winners.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand batsman, Glenn Turner was the top run-scorer for the tournament with 333 runs, whilst Australian bowler Gary Gilmour was the top wicket-taker with 11 wickets despite only playing in the final two matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral cricket competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was played between the three test nations at the time – England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The concept was later dropped because of inclement weather and a lack of public interest.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first one-day match to occur was in 1962 when four English county cricket teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was won by Northamptonshire who defeated Leicestershire by five wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The limited-over format had been used in what sponsors marketed as a 'World Cricket Cup' in England in 1966 and 1967, contested between England, a Rest of the World XI, and a touring team (the West Indies in 1966 and Pakistan in 1967).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The marketing of the event was clearly influenced by the hosting of the 1966 FIFA World Cup in the same country.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The 1966 'World Cricket Cup' was won by England, that in 1967 by the Rest of the World.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] A report in the *Cricketer* implied that the last such match in this "Triangular Tournament", between Pakistan and the Rest of the World was neither well-attended nor taken entirely seriously: "It was a pity that a larger crowd was not present ...
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Sobers took the Cup and the World Xl took the gold medals.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was not until 1971 that the first official One Day International (ODI) took place at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) as a replacement for the third test of the 1970–71 Ashes series between Australia and England.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to a deluge of rain that had affected the match for the first three days of the test.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match was a forty over match with each over being eight deliveries.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After England made 190 from 39.4 overs, Australia chased the target at a steady rate to secure the match with 42 balls remaining.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Two years later at Lord's during the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, plans were made for a men's tournament to take place in 1975.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was planned to involve all the Test nations at the time in two group stages with the top two in each group qualifying for the knockout stage with the final at Lord's.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The format of the 1975 Cricket World Cup had the eight teams split into two groups of four, with each team playing the others in their group once.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played over 60 overs per side with group stage matches scheduled to take place between 7 and 14 June.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played entirely during day, with a cut off time of 7.30 pm.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Three days were allocated to each match with each able to be continued if they were halted for rain or bad light.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group advanced to the semi-finals on 18 June, with the winners qualifying for the final at Lord's on 21 June.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams were invited to compete at the World Cup: the six full members of the International Cricket Conference (ICC), and two other teams – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] South Africa was not allowed to complete due to the sporting boycott of the country which took place during apartheid era, the ICC having placed a moratorium on tours of the country in 1970.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began the teams were split into two groups.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The ICC made the decision to place the two teams which were not Test playing countries in separate groups.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] They also decided to place England and Australia in separate groups and to do the same with India and Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Six grounds were used to host matches during the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The announcement of venues began on 26 July 1973 when the ICC announced that the tournament would be played, with Lord's as the venue for the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The remaining venues were announced on 5 November 1974, with the scheduling for the tournament announced alongside that for the five county cricket tournaments that would take place during the 1975 season.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Other than Lord's, which hosted only one group stage match, and The Oval which hosted three, each of the grounds was used for two matches during the group stage.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Headingley and The Oval were the grounds chosen for the two semi-finals.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began each team named a squad of 14 players.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Heading into the first Cricket World Cup, the Ladbrokes betting agency had the West Indies as the favourites at 9–4.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was followed by England at 11–4 with Pakistan and Australia in third and fourth respectively.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] East Africa was last in the betting odds at 1500–1.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the tournament, most of the teams played in warm-up matches against English county teams to get used to the English conditions with most of the national teams getting wins.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only East Africa, Sri Lanka and India lost at least one warm-up match before the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia played in Canada, losing to Eastern Canada and drawing with Toronto, before heading to England.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight days before the World Cup, the ICC declared in a unanimous decision that any of the balls that went over a batsman's head would be called wide due to the fast short-pitched bowling.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 7 June with four matches being played.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match at Lord's saw England deliver the highest score by a team in the 60 over match with 334 runs being scored.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Dennis Amiss top scored for the English with 137 from 147 balls helped by Keith Fletcher and Chris Old who each recorded a half-century.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Sunil Gavaskar batted through the entire innings for only 36 runs off 174 balls, prompting Gulabrai Ramchand to speculate that he was treating the match as batting practice.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia opened their campaign with a win against Pakistan at Headingley with a 73-run victory.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to Dennis Lillee's five-wicket haul which brought Pakistan's hope of a win crashing down as they collapsed from 181 for four to be all out for 205.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Earlier, Ross Edwards top scored for Australia with 80 as he aided the Australians in getting 94 runs from the last 13 overs to bring Australia to 278 for seven from their 60 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other two matches saw easy wins for the West Indies and New Zealand.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Glenn Turner, he occupied the crease during the whole New Zealand innings as he top scored with 171 as New Zealand won by 181 runs over East Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies took a nine-wicket victory over Sri Lanka who became the first team to score under 100 runs in a One Day International.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Despite missing two players due to operation – Asif Iqbal – and examinations – Imran Khan – Pakistan was not fazed by the missing players in the second round of games with the team scoring 266 for seven from their 60 overs with standing captain Majid Khan top scoring for Pakistan with 60.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies fell to 166 for eight which included a period of three wickets for only 10 runs as Bernard Julien, Clive Lloyd and Keith Boyce all losing their wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] But the last wicket pair of Deryck Murray and Andy Roberts stole the match away as the West Indies won by a wicket off the final over.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] On the field, Alan Turner scored a century as Australia ended with 328 with Sri Lanka falling 52 runs short as John Mason from *The Daily Telegraph* stated that they might not have many new admirers with their short ball stuff sending two Sri Lankan batsman to hospital.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Group A saw two convincing wins to England and India.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] At Trent Bridge, Keith Fletcher top scored for England with 131 as he guided the English to their second victory and going to the lead of the group table with an 80-run win over New Zealand.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other match in Group A saw 720 spectators observe India record a 10-wicket victory with Madan Lal taking three wickets for India, after East Africa were all-out for only 120.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the match sold out four days in advance, the West Indies took on Australia to see who would finish top of Group B.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the ball swinging in the air, the pair of Rod Marsh and Ross Edwards guided Australia to 192 with a 99-run partnership for the sixth wicket after Australia fell to 61/5.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies went on to take a seven-wicket victory with Alvin Kallicharran top scoring with 78, which included a period of 31 runs of nine Dennis Lillee deliveries as the West Indies finished top of Group B.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan ended their tournament with a 192-run victory over Sri Lanka at Trent Bridge with half centuries to Zaheer Abbas, Majid Khan and Sadiq Mohammad.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, New Zealand sealed their spot in the semi-finals with a four-wicket victory over India off the back of a century from Glenn Turner as he hit twelve fours on his way to an unbeaten innings of 114.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only Ramesh Sethi offered much resistance, lasting for 32 overs to score 30.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The knockout stage of the Cricket World Cup consisted of two single-elimination rounds leading to a final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] If the match was delayed due to rain there were two reserve days to play out the match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first semi-final was between England and Australia at Headingley.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Australia, their one change in bringing in Gary Gilmour for Ashley Mallett proved critical in booking Australia's spot into the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to the grassy pitch that both captains would criticise after the match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia elected to field first, Gilmour took six wickets for 14 runs as he had England at 37 for seven after he bowled his 12 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Mike Denness attempted to bring England back but would lose his wicket as England fell for 93.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In the run-chase, Australia collapsed to 39 for six before Gilmour partnered with Doug Walters as they chased the remaining runs to earn Australia a berth in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final was between the West Indies and New Zealand at The Oval.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Batting first, New Zealand reached 92 for only one loss at the lunch break.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After lunch though, they collapsed to 158 with Geoff Howarth top scoring for New Zealand with 51, while Bernard Julien was the top wicket taker with four wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The final match on 21 June was sold out three days beforehand.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the West Indies being favourites for the match, they were asked by Ian Chappell to bat first and would go on to score 291 for eight wickets from 60 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After being given a second chance from a Ross Edwards dropped chance at mid-wicket, Clive Lloyd went on to top score for the West Indies with 102.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Gary Gilmour was the best of the Australian bowlers with five wickets for 48 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Ian Chappell scored a half-century to set up the foundation for Australia before three run-outs from the hands of Viv Richards put the pressure on Australia as they collapsed to 233 for nine.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] A final-wicket partnership of 41 from Dennis Lillee and Jeff Thomson brought Australia within 18 runs of victory.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] But a fifth run-out of the innings saw Australia bowled out for 274 and would see the West Indies win by 17 runs, claiming the first men's World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Glenn Turner of New Zealand ended the tournament as the leading run scorer for the 1975 edition with his 333 runs coming in four games which included an unbeaten 171 against East Africa, which was also the highest score of the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In second place was English player Dennis Amiss with Pakistan's Majid Khan rounding out the top three.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australian player Gary Gilmour was the tournament's leading wicket taker with 11 wickets from his two games, which included the best tournament figures in the semi-finals when he took six wickets for 14 against England.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Bernard Julien and Keith Boyce (both from the West Indies) finished in second place, both getting 10 wickets for the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The **1979 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '79**) was the second edition of the Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference, it was held in England from 9 to 23 June 1979.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was once again sponsored by the Prudential Assurance Company and had eight teams participating in the tournament with the only change being Canada who qualified with Sri Lanka in the qualifier for the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The format remained the same with two teams qualifying from each group with the final once again being at Lord's.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England joined first-time semi-finalists Pakistan as the qualifiers from Group A, while the West Indies finished top of Group B ahead of New Zealand.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] After the West Indies and England both won their semi-finals over Pakistan and New Zealand, respectively, they met in the final at Lord's with the West Indies defending their title from four years earlier with a 92-run victory.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] West Indian batsman, Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs from four matches with English player Mike Hendrick ending up as the leading wicket-taker with ten wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The eight teams at the tournament were split into two groups of four teams, with each team playing the others in their group in a single round-robin format.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group then advance to the semi-finals to play in a single-elimination tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 tournament saw the first qualifiers in a World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 ICC Trophy was held during late May and early June at various grounds in the English Midlands, with the two finalists qualifying for the World Cup where they joined the six Test nations who qualified automatically.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Sri Lanka and Canada qualified after defeating Denmark and Bermuda respectively in the semi-finals.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 9 June with four matches being played.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England took on Australia at Lord's and after the home team elected to field first, restricted the Australians to 97 for one with fine fielding and bowling.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] After Andrew Hilditch dragged his second ball after lunch into the stumps, the Australians would be restricted for 159 which included four run-outs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The run-chase saw Mike Brearley and Graham Gooch control the innings and led England to a six wicket victory.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] In a very close semi-final match, England prevailed.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England began badly, falling to 38/2, before Mike Brearley (53 from 115 balls, 3 fours) and Graham Gooch (71 from 84 balls, 1 four, 3 sixes) resurrected the innings.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Derek Randall (42 from 50 balls, 1 four, 1 six) played well in the second half of the innings, as England recovered from 98/4 to post 221 (8 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] In the response, John Wright (69 from 137 balls) attacked well in the beginning.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of wickets bogged New Zealand down, and despite several late flourishes in the batting order, New Zealand started to drop behind.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] When New Zealand could not achieve the remaining 14 runs from the last over of the match, England went into the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge (73 from 107 balls, 5 fours, 1 six) and Desmond Haynes (65 from 115 balls, 4 fours) set a first wicket partnership of 132 runs in a match dominated by batting.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards and Clive Lloyd also contributed solidly, as West Indies ran up 293 (6 wickets, 60 overs) against Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Majid Khan (81 from 124 balls, 7 fours) and Zaheer Abbas (93 from 122 balls) shared a second-wicket partnership of 166 runs in 36 overs in the response.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, none of the other Pakistani batsmen flourished, with Javed Miandad being bowled for a duck first ball, and Pakistan lost 9/74, beginning with the dismissal of Abbas.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan was bowled out for 250 in 56.2 overs in the high-scoring semi-final, sending the West Indies to the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England won the toss and chose to field first.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies got off to a bad start, falling to 99/4 with the loss of Greenidge, Haynes, Kallicharan, and captain Clive Lloyd.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, Vivian Richards (138 from 157 balls, 11 fours, 3 sixes) and Collis King (86 from 66 balls, 10 fours, 3 sixes) consolidated the innings.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] King especially savaged the English bowling, with a strike rate of 130.3.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies were 238/5 when the 139 run partnership ended with King’s dismissal.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards and the tail then took the West Indies to a very imposing total of 286 (9 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The English batsmen got off to a good start.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] But the openers, Mike Brearley (64 from 130 balls, 7 fours) and Geoff Boycott (57 from 105 balls, 3 fours) scored very slowly with a methodical opening partnership of 129 runs in 38 overs, playing as if the match were a five-day Test.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] By the time both batsmen were out, the required run rate had risen too high, putting pressure on the later batsmen.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Graham Gooch played some hefty strokes in scoring his 32, taking England to 183/2.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of Derek Randall triggered a batting collapse in which England lost their last eight wickets for 11 runs to finish all out for 194 in 51 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards was declared Man of the Match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs coming from his four games.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Second was fellow West Indian player, Viv Richards who finished with 217 runs from four games which included the highest individual score of the tournament of 138 in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Graham Gooch from England rounded out the top three.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Mike Hendrick from England was the leading wicket taker for the tournament with ten wickets from five matches with a three-way tie for second place with Brian McKechnie (New Zealand), Asif Iqbal (Pakistan) and Chris Old each taking nine wickets for the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The total attendance at the tournament was 132,000, including 25,000 at the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The **1983 Cricket World Cup** (officially the **Prudential Cup '83**) was the third edition of the Cricket World Cup tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] It was held from 9 to 25 June 1983 in England and Wales and was won by India.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Eight countries participated in the event.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] England, India, Pakistan and West Indies qualified for the semi-finals.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The preliminary matches were played in two groups of four teams each, and each country played the others in its group twice.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams in each group qualified for the semi-finals.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The matches consisted of 60 overs per innings and were played in traditional white clothing and with red balls.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The eight teams at the tournament were divided into two groups of four, and each team would play the others in their group twice.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group then advanced to the semi-finals, which were played as a single-elimination tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Every game was 60 overs a team, and there were no day/night matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams qualified for the final tournament (seven full ICC members, including recently appointed full member Sri Lanka, and Zimbabwe, who qualified by winning the 1982 ICC Trophy).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Unlike in previous Cricket World Cups, the group stages were played in a double round robin format.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Group A comprised the hosts England, Pakistan, New Zealand and Sri Lanka; while Group B contained reigning champions West Indies, India, Australia, and the sole qualifier Zimbabwe.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Unlike in later World Cups, with formats designed such that all games could be screened live on television, matches took place simultaneously at multiple venues, with matches played every other day and a reserve day in case of rain, although only three of the matches required a second day.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, England started strongly with a 106 run victory over New Zealand at The Oval, scoring an imposing 322/6 in their innings, driven by a partnership of 115 in 16 overs between Allan Lamb and Mike Gatting.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan also started with a win, by 50 runs over Sri Lanka, despite being hampered throughout the tournament by Imran Khan being unfit to bowl, after scoring 338/5 in 60 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] England's second group match brought a second win, as David Gower's 130, including five sixes and 12 fours, powered a 47 run win over Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Meanwhile, New Zealand beat Pakistan by 52 runs despite Abdul Qadir's 4/21 in 12 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] England then beat Pakistan by 8 wickets with nearly ten overs to spare at Lord's, while Richard Hadlee's 5/25 saw Sri Lanka bowled out for 206, New Zealand getting home with over 20 overs to spare.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] England's only defeat of the group stages came in the fourth round of matches, against New Zealand, off the penultimate ball of the New Zealand innings.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan triumphed over Sri Lanka, once again led by Abdul Qadir (5/44).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The fifth round of matches on 18 June saw England seal their place in the semi-final, with a first wicket partnership of 115 between Graeme Fowler and Chris Tavaré alone scoring nearly half of Pakistan's 232.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Meanwhile, New Zealand failed to secure passage to the knockout stage, losing to Sri Lanka in a low scoring affair.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the final round of matches, England beat Sri Lanka by 9 wickets in a match with no implications for the final table.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The match between New Zealand and Pakistan would decide the second qualifier.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Any win by New Zealand would be sufficient to see them qualify; Pakistan had not only to win, but do so by a sufficient margin to overhaul New Zealand's average run rate.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] An 11 run victory for Pakistan proved sufficient, as Zaheer Abbas made an unbeaten 103 before New Zealand were bowled out.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Group B started with the first shock of the tournament, as Zimbabwe beat Australia in what Wisden described as "a bigger surprise than any in the previous two world cups".
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Duncan Fletcher led the way, making 69* and being awarded man of the match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Wet weather in the second round of games played on 11 June led to low scores.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] West Indies scored 252/9 in their innings, which stretched over two days, against Australia; in response, Australia were bowled out for 151 in just 30.3 overs, an effort not helped by Graeme Wood being taken to hospital with severe concussion after being hit by Michael Holding.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] India comfortably beat Zimbabwe by 5 wickets in the contemporaneous fixture.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Two days later, Australia defeated India by 162 runs, with man of the match Trevor Chappell scoring 110 off 131 balls and Ken MacLeay taking 6/39.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The other match that day was also a one-sided affair, as West Indies restricted Zimbabwe to just 217/7 in their 60 overs, despite Duncan Fletcher scoring another unbeaten half century, and then romped home with a partnership of 195 for the third wicket between Gordon Greenidge and Larry Gomes.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the first of the return fixtures, West Indies overcame India by 66 runs, with Viv Richards making 119; for the second time in the tournament, an opposing batsman retired hurt, as Dilip Vengsarkar was the unlucky batsman on this occasion, hit in the mouth by Malcolm Marshall.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Australia beat Zimbabwe by 32 runs to level their account in the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] West Indies qualified for the semi-finals with a match to spare, beating Australia by 7 wickets substantially due to a partnership of 124 for the second wicket between Greenidge and Richards.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] That left West Indies versus Zimbabwe as a dead rubber, and West Indies duly won by ten wickets with nearly fifteen overs to spare.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The final group B match was a straightforward tussle for qualification between Australia and India.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] However, after India had made 247 all out, in a team effort where the highest score was 40 and there were 37 extras, Australia collapsed to 129 all out, with Madan Lal and Roger Binny taking four wickets each.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the first semi-final, at Old Trafford on 22 June, England won the toss and elected to bat.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The English batsmen mistimed many balls and used the bat's edge frequently, as the restrictive Indian bowling led England to score 213 (all out, 60 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Graeme Fowler (33 from 59 balls, 3 fours) top scored, and Kapil Dev took 3 for 35 in eleven overs, with Mohinder Amarnath and Roger Binny taking two wickets each.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] In reply, Yashpal Sharma (61 from 115 balls, 3 fours, 2 sixes) and Sandeep Patil (51 from 32 balls, 8 fours) made half-centuries, as India reached their target in 54.4 overs, winning by 6 wickets in a classic victory over the previous tournament's runners-up.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Mohinder Amarnath (46 from 92 balls, 4 fours, 1 six) picked up the man-of-the-match award for his all round performance, which saw him add 46 runs to his earlier bowling success (2/27 in 12 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final, between Pakistan and the West Indies, was staged at The Oval on the same day.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] West Indies won the toss and invited Pakistan to bat, whom they restricted to just 184 (8 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Mohsin Khan (70 from 176 balls, 1 four) fought his way past 50 against the formidable West Indies bowling attack (he was the only Pakistani batsman to reach 50).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Malcolm Marshall (3/28) and Andy Roberts (2/25) starred with the ball.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the final, India lost the toss and were asked to bat first against the West Indies.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Only Krishnamachari Srikkanth (38 from 57 balls) and Mohinder Amarnath (26 from 80 balls) put up any significant resistance as Roberts, Marshall, Joel Garner and Michael Holding ripped through the Indian batsmen, ably supported by Gomes.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Surprising resistance by the tail allowed India to compile 183 (all out, 54.4 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Sandeep Patil and Madan Lal saved the game to get the team past the 150-run mark at a critical point in the match where India scored 183 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Without those two batsmen, India's score would have been lower.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] The Indian bowling exploited the weather and pitch conditions perfectly to bowl out the West Indies for 140 from 52 overs, winning by 43 runs and completing one of the most stunning upsets in cricket history.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] It still remains the lowest ever total successfully defended in a World Cup final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Amarnath and Madan Lal each took three wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Viv Richards, was West Indies' top scorer with 33 from 28 balls.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Kant was the most economical bowler, conceding 0 runs from his two overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] Amarnath was once again awarded the Man of the Match award for his all-round performance.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1983-cricket-world-cup] There was no 'Man of the Series' awarded in 1983.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1984-asia-cup] The **1984 Asia Cup** (also known as the **Rothmans Asia Cup**) was the inaugural edition of the Asia Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1984-asia-cup] It was held in Sharjah, UAE, which was the location of the newly formed Asian Cricket Council.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1984-asia-cup] The new tournament was held between April 6–13, in 1984 and three teams took part: India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1984-asia-cup] The Sharjah Cricket Association Stadium hosted its first One Day International (ODI) match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1984-asia-cup] The 1984 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other once.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1984-asia-cup] India won both its matches, winning the inaugural Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1984-asia-cup] Sri Lanka came in second while Pakistan lost both its matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] The **1986 Asia Cup** (also known as the **John Player Asia Cup 86**) was the second Asia Cup tournament, and was held in Sri Lanka between March 30 and April 6.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] Three teams took part in the tournament: Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Asian leading associate member Bangladesh.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] India pulled out of the tournament due to strained cricketing relations with Sri Lanka and was replaced by Asian leading associate nation Bangladesh, which had qualified by winning the 1984 South-East Asia Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] The 1986 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other once, and the top two teams qualifying for a place in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] Pakistan won both its matches and qualified for the final against Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] Sri Lanka beat Pakistan to win their first Asia Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] The First South-East Asian Cricket Tournament was held in Dhaka in January 1984.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] Two teams from the host country were joined by teams from Singapore and Hong Kong.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] The Bangladesh national team won the trophy, and thus qualified for the 1986 Asia Cup in Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] The organizers suffered an early setback when Malaysia, one of the stronger cricketing nations of the Far East, withdrew at the last moment.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] Apart from Dhaka, Chittagong and Mymensingh hosted some games.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1986-asia-cup] The Bangladesh national team, however, played all its fixtures at the capital.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The **1987 Cricket World Cup** (officially known as the **Reliance Cup 1987** for sponsorship reasons) was the fourth Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] It was held from 8 October to 8 November 1987 in India and Pakistan – the first such tournament to be held outside England.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The one-day format was unchanged from the eight-team 1983 event except for a reduction in the number of overs a team played from 60 to 50, the current standard for all ODIs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The competition was won, for the first time, by Australia who defeated their arch-rivals England by seven runs in the second-most closely fought World Cup final to date in Kolkata's Eden Gardens stadium.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The two host nations, India and Pakistan failed to reach the final, after both being eliminated in the semi-finals.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies failed to live up to expectations and did not advance from the group stage.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The format of the competition was two groups of four teams each team playing each other twice in 50-over matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group would advance to the semi-finals where the two winners would then advance to the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] All matches were played during daytime and– for the final time in the tournament's history– saw the teams appear in traditional white clothing and use traditional red balls as used in Test/First Class matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The ICC decreed that all seven eligible countries holding Test status would automatically qualify for the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] One additional place would be awarded to the winners of the 1986 ICC Trophy.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] For the second consecutive tournament this was Zimbabwe, who defeated the Netherlands.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Australia won the toss and chose to bat.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The Australian batsmen got off to a very good start, and they scored fluently, with David Boon (65 from 91 balls, 4 fours) top scoring, and making an 82 run second-wicket partnership with DM Jones.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Australia were looking to reach 300 with strong batting before Imran Khan took 3 wickets for 17 runs in 5 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Australia lost 4/31, but a high number of extras (34) from the Pakistani bowlers, as well as the solid batting from earlier on, brought Australia to 267 (8 wickets, 50 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan started badly, falling to 3/38.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Imran Khan (58 from 84 balls, 4 fours) and Javed Miandad (70 from 103 balls, 4 fours) shared a partnership of 112 runs in 26 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] However, with the required run rate at 7.87 runs when Miandad fell, there was just too much for the upcoming batsmen to do, and Pakistan lost 6/99 as they were bowled all out for 249 (all out, 49 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Earlier Steve Waugh scored 18 runs off the 50th over bowled by Saleem Jaffar and ironically Pakistan lost the match by 18 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] After reaching 2/79, Graham Gooch (115 from 136 balls, 11 fours) and captain Mike Gatting (56 from 62 balls, 5 fours) shared a partnership of 117 runs in 19 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] After Gooch was finally stumped, 51 more runs were added, and England reached 254 (6 wickets, 50 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] India made a bad start, falling to 3/73.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The middle order scored fluently, with Mohammed Azharuddin, (64 from 74 balls, 7 fours) top scoring.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Before Azharuddin was removed lbw by Eddie Hemmings, India were at 5/204, needing 50 runs from the last 10 overs, with 5 wickets in hand, and it looked like it would be a very close game.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] However, the middle and tailend order for India collapsed, as India lost 5/15.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] India were eventually bowled all out for 219 (all out, 45.3 overs), giving England both a berth in the final and a measure of revenge for the loss they suffered to India in the semi-final of the World Cup four years earlier in England.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] David Boon (75 from 125 balls, 7 fours) top-scored for Australia, whose batsmen scored fluently.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Australia posted 253 (5 wickets, 50 overs).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Mike Veletta (45 from 31 balls, 6 fours) cut loose late in the innings, as Australia scored 65 runs from the last six overs of their innings.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] In the English reply, opener Tim Robinson was out LBW for a first ball duck.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] Allan Lamb (45 from 55 balls, 4 fours) also posted a great innings, but it was in vain as the required run-rate for England began to rise.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] When England failed to score the last 17 runs from the final over, the cup went to Australia.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] The first hat-trick in Cricket World Cup history was taken by Chetan Sharma of India during their final group match against New Zealand.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1987-cricket-world-cup] He clean bowled Ken Rutherford, Ian Smith and Ewen Chatfield with the last three balls of the 42nd over.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1988-asia-cup] The **1988 Asia Cup** (also known as the **Wills Asia Cup**) was the third Asia Cup tournament, held in Bangladesh between 26 October and 4 November 1988.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1988-asia-cup] Four teams took part in the tournament: India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and the host nation Bangladesh.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1988-asia-cup] The matches were the first-ever List A-classified being played in Bangladesh, then an Associate Member of the International Cricket Council (ICC), their opponents all being Full Members.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1988-asia-cup] The 1988 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other three once, and the top two teams qualifying for a place in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/1988-asia-cup] India and Sri Lanka qualified for the final in which India defeated Sri Lanka by 6 wickets to win its second Asia Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The **Afghanistan men's national cricket team** (Pashto: د افغانستان کرکټ ملي لوب‌‌‌‌‌‌ډله, ) represents Afghanistan in international cricket.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] It is a full member of the International Cricket Council (ICC) with Test, One-Day International and T20 International status.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Cricket has been played in Afghanistan since the mid-19th century, but it was only in the early 21st century that the national team began to enjoy success.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Afghanistan Cricket Board was formed in 1995, becoming an affiliate member of the ICC in 2001 and a member of the cricket confederation, Asian Cricket Council (ACC) in 2003.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] After nearly a decade of playing international cricket, on 22 June 2017 full ICC membership (and therefore Test status) was granted to Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Alongside Ireland, this took the number of Test cricket playing nations to twelve.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In view of the persistent conflict and insecurity in Afghanistan, following this status, the team moved to a new home ground in Dehradun, in India.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The current home ground of the Afghanistan men's cricket team is the Sharjah Cricket Stadium in the UAE.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Cricket has grown in popularity in Afghanistan, and the national team has gained international recognition through its participation in major tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Media Coverage linked the sport's rise to broader social interest in cricket within the country.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Cricket in Afghanistan gained traction by Afghan expatriates who learnt the sport while living in Pakistan in the 1980s and 1990s, during the post-Soviet invasion era.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Most members of the early Afghanistan national cricket team grew up in Pakistan and participated in the country's domestic cricket structure, making use of cricket facilities in Peshawar with the support of the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] It was during this time that the Afghanistan Cricket Federation (now ACB) was also founded, in 1995.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Like all sports, cricket was initially banned by the Taliban, but cricket became an exception in 2000 (being the only sport in Afghanistan to be approved by the Taliban).
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The ACF received recognition from the International Cricket Council (ICC) in 2001.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan fielded their cricket team in Pakistan's domestic setup for the first time in the 2001–02 season, participating in the second division of the Quaid-e-Azam Trophy where they drew two and lost three of their five games.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They returned for the Cornelius Trophy in the 2002–03 season, drawing one and losing three matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the 2003–04 season, they made an appearance in the PCB's inter-district tournament in Peshawar, where they registered their lone victory against Swabi, drew twice and lost two matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They began playing in Asian regional tournaments in 2004, finishing sixth in their first ACC Trophy.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] More success began in 2006 when they were runners-up to Bahrain in the Middle East Cup and beat an MCC team featuring former England captain Mike Gatting by 171 runs in Mumbai.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They toured England in the summer of 2006, winning six out of seven matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Three of their wins came against the second XIs of Essex, Glamorgan and Leicestershire.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They finished third in the ACC Trophy that year, beating Nepal in a play-off match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They won their first tournament in 2007, sharing the ACC Twenty20 Cup with Oman after the two tied in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They began their qualifying campaign for the 2011 World Cup in Jersey in 2008, winning Division Five of the World Cricket League.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They finished third in the ACC Trophy Elite tournament the same year, and won a second consecutive WCL tournament, Division Four in Tanzania later in the year.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Afghanistan national team was coached by former Pakistani cricketers Kabir Khan and Rashid Latif in its initial years.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] During this period, a number of Afghan international cricketers made appearances for Pakistani domestic outfits in the first-class circuit.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In January 2009, Afghanistan progressed to the 2009 World Cup Qualifier by winning Division Three of the World Cricket League in Buenos Aires, topping the table on net run rate ahead of Uganda and Papua New Guinea.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2010, Afghanistan competed at the Asian Games, a non-ICC T20 event hosted by China, where they defeated a second-string Pakistan team by 22 runs in the semi-finals in what was considered an upset.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In May 2011, the Afghan team embarked on a tour of Pakistan to partake in a three-match limited overs series against Pakistan A, where they were whitewashed by the home team 3–0.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They followed this up with another tour in September to participate in Pakistan's domestic National T20 Cup in Karachi as the Afghan Cheetahs, but had another poor outing, losing all three of their matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the 2011 Cricket World Cup qualifying tournament, Afghanistan failed to progress to the World Cup, but earned ODI status for four years.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Their first ODI was against Scotland in the 5th place playoff, having previously beaten the Scots earlier in the tournament; Afghanistan won by 89 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan became the only affiliate member to have ODI status.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the Intercontinental Cup Afghanistan played its first first-class match against a Zimbabwe XI in a four-day match in Mutare.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] During the match, which was drawn, Afghan batsman Noor Ali scored centuries in both his innings, making him only the fourth player to do so on their first-class debut.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Later, in August 2009, they played the Netherlands in the same competition at the VRA Cricket Ground, winning a low-scoring match by one wicket.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan then took part in the 2009 ACC Twenty20 Cup in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan was drawn in Group A, which Afghanistan topped at the end of the group stages by winning all five of their matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the semi-finals the Afghans defeated Kuwait by 8 wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the final they met the hosts, the United Arab Emirates, whom they defeated by 84 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 1 February 2010, Afghanistan played their first Twenty20 International against Ireland, which they lost by 5 wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 13 February 2010, Afghanistan defeated the United Arab Emirates by 4 wickets to make their way to the 2010 ICC World Twenty20 to be in the West Indies in April 2010.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Later the same day, they defeated Ireland by 8 wickets in the Final of 2010 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier to win the qualifier.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan were in Group C of the main tournament, with India and South Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] During their first match against India, opening batsman Noor Ali hit 50 runs, helping Afghanistan to a score of 115 in their 20 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Despite this they lost the match by 8 wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In their second match, the team were reduced to 14/6 at one stage, before a late rally from Mirwais Ashraf and Hamid Hassan helped Afghanistan post 88 all out, resulting in a loss by 59 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The team's Intercontinental Cup campaign continued in 2010, with wins over Ireland, Canada, Scotland and Kenya before they beat Scotland by 7 wickets in the final in Dubai.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Also in 2010, they won the ACC Trophy Elite tournament in Kuwait, beating Nepal in the final and finished third in Division One of the World Cricket League in the Netherlands.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They took part in the cricket tournament at the 2010 Asian Games in China and won the silver medal, losing to Bangladesh in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2011, Afghanistan begun the 2011-13 ICC World Cricket League Championship.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the parallel one-day league, they won two matches against Canada and lost twice to the UAE.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In December once again took part in the ACC Twenty20 Cup, this time in Nepal.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They went on to win all of their matches to once again take the Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 10 February 2012, Afghanistan played a one-off One Day International (ODI) match against Pakistan at Sharjah, the first ever official game between the two teams and also the first ever ODI between an Affiliate and a Test-playing nation.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Billed as a historic occasion for Afghan cricket, the game was won comfortably by Pakistan by seven wickets with 13 overs to spare.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They also took on the Australia Cricket Team in an Only ODI at Sharjah in August 2012.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They fell short in both matches, but their performance showed they were continuing to make progress.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Their 2012 ICC International Cup games were also challenging, resulting in a split with the Netherlands and a loss to Ireland.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] 2013 brought greater success for Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In March, they played two T20 Internationals against Scotland in UAE and prevailed in both matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They also won two ODIs in the World Cricket League Championship against the same opponents.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the WCL Championship table, as 2013 dawned Afghanistan was level with Scotland in third, trailing Ireland and the Netherlands for the two automatic qualification spots for the 2015 World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] However, two convincing wins in spring over Scotland boosted hopes some.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Then in July the Netherlands failed to take any points against Ireland, leaving Afghanistan in a position to qualify if they could win their final four matches against poorer performing Namibia and Kenya.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Despite the United Arab Emirates and the Netherlands both being able to win their remaining games, keeping the pressure on Afghanistan, Afghanistan handled Namibia, then defeated Kenya by 8 wickets on 2 October.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] With one final win over Kenya on 4 October by 7 wickets, Afghanistan secured second in the Championship with 19 points, and qualified for World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan also crushed Scotland in their one-day ICC Intercontinental Cup league in March in Abu Dhabi: Afghanistan (275: Shah 67*, Davey 4–53) beat Scotland (125: Taylor 48*, Dawlatzai 6–57 and 145: Coetzer 57, Dawlatzai 5–37) by an innings and 5 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Izatullah Dawlatzai took eleven wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In July 2014, Afghanistan toured Zimbabwe to play its 1st full series against a full member.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The 4 match ODI series finished 2–2 and the 2 match first-class series finished 1–1.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] With their victory over Zimbabwe on 25 December 2015, Afghanistan entered the top 10 of the ICC's ODI rankings for the first time.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan became an Affiliate member of the ICC in 2001.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Then in 2009 it had attained one-day status until 2015.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2012, the Asian Cricket Council decided to nominate Afghanistan for Associate membership with the ICC, with the request being looked into at the ICC's annual conference in June.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In March 2013, Afghanistan received a further support boost when a two-year Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) was signed between the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) and Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) for the development of Afghanistan cricket ahead of the 2015 World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The PCB provided technical and professional support, including game-education programmes, coaching courses, skill and performance analysis, and basic umpiring and curator courses.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] High performance camps for emerging players were also organised.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The PCB-regulated National Cricket Academy (NCA) helped in improving technical, tactical, mental and physical skills and hosted lectures on doping, anti-corruption and various codes of conduct.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In April 2013, the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) was also allocated US$422,000 (22,400,000 AFN approx.) from the ICC's targeted assistance and performance programme.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The world governing body of cricket approved the grant at its IDI (ICC Development International) board meeting, which concluded in Dubai.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The money, to be given over three years, was aimed at developing more competitive teams among ICC Full, Associate and Affiliate members.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Previous countries to receive similar funding programmes included the Netherlands, Scotland, the West Indies, Zimbabwe and Ireland.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] An ICC statement suggested the funding was targeted towards the development of the National Cricket Academy in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Qualification for the tournament was a historic feat for cricket in Afghanistan, one amplified by the fact that the team included many players who picked up the game in refugee camps outside their war-torn country.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan made their World Cup debut in the 2015 Cricket World Cup in which their first game was against Bangladesh at the Manuka Oval in Canberra, Australia.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 26 February 2015, Afghanistan won their first World Cup match against Scotland, winning by one wicket.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The team, however, lost all its remaining games and was knocked out of the tournament in the opening round.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The 2019 Cricket World Cup was the second Cricket World Cup in which Afghanistan participated in, and the first consecutive World Cup appearance for the time.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] This World Cup was in a "round robin" format where Afghanistan faced all the other teams but did not manage to claim victory against any national team in the tournament for the first time in their short history in the World Cup tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the 2023 Cricket World Cup, Afghanistan secured a victory by 69 runs against the defending champions, England, in their third match of the World Cup on 15 October 2023.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] This was the first time Afghanistan defeated England and the first time Afghanistan defeated the defending Cricket World Cup champions.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They also defeated Pakistan in ODI cricket for the first time.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They also defeated Sri Lanka for the first time in the Cricket World Cup by 7 wickets on 30 October 2023.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] This was also the first time in a Cricket World Cup that Afghanistan had won two matches consecutively.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the following match, they defeated the Netherlands for the first time in the Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] This was the first time Afghanistan achieved three consecutive victories in the Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The team visited Zimbabwe for the second time in October, where Afghanistan clinched a historic one-day international series over Zimbabwe after a 73-run victory in Bulawayo saw them win 3–2.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In doing so, they became the first non-Test-playing country to win a multi-game bilateral ODI series against a Test team.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Afghanistan cricket team toured the United Arab Emirates to play the United Arab Emirates cricket team in December 2016.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The tour consisted of three Twenty20 International (T20I) matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Afghanistan cricket team toured Bangladesh in September and October 2016 to play three One Day Internationals (ODIs) matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] This was Afghanistan's first full series against a Test-playing team other than Zimbabwe and was the first bilateral series between the two teams.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Ahead of the ODI series, there was a fifty-over warm-up game between the Bangladesh Cricket Board XI and Afghanistan in Fatullah.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan won the warm-up match by 66 runs and Bangladesh won the ODI series 2–1.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In February 2017 the International Cricket Council (ICC) awarded first-class status to Afghanistan's four-day domestic competition.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Afghan cricket team toured Zimbabwe between January and February 2017.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The tour consisted of five One Day International (ODI) matches.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Prior to the ODI series, the Afghanistan A cricket team played five "unofficial" ODI matches against the Zimbabwe A cricket team.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] All of those matches had been designated List A status.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan won the initial List A series 4–1 and the ODI series 3–2.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Ireland cricket team toured India during March 2017 to participate in a series of matches against Afghanistan, consisting of three T20 matches, five ODI contests and an ICC Intercontinental Cup match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] All the matches took place in Greater Noida.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Afghan team were highly successful, emerging victorious in both the T20I series 3–0 and the ODI series 3–2.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan also won the ICC Intercontinental Cup match, by the margin of an innings and 172 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Afghanistan cricket team completed another tour in June 2017, this time facing the West Indies.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The tour marked Afghanistan's first bilateral tour against a full member nation other than Zimbabwe.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] (Later that month, Afghanistan itself was awarded that status.) The tour was less successful for the Afghans, who were convincingly defeated 3–0 in the T20 series.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They performed better in the ODI series, seizing a 1–1 draw after the final match was washed out with no result.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan registered their first win against Sri Lanka in Asia Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan qualified for 2012 ICC World Twenty20 held in Sri Lanka as the runner-up of the ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier and joined India and England in the group stage.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the first match against India on 19 September, Afghanistan won the toss and elected to field.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] India posted 159/5 in 20 overs but Afghanistan fell short of that target by scoring 136 in 19.3 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In the second match against England on 21 September, Afghanistan won the toss and again elected to field.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] England set a target of 196/5 (20 overs) but Afghanistan were all out for 80 in 17.2 overs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] England and India qualified for the Super Eights and Afghanistan was eliminated as a result of this match.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 3 October 2013, Afghanistan beat Kenya to finish second in the WCL Championship and qualify for the 2015 Cricket World Cup, becoming the 20th team to gain entry into the tournament overall.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan secured their passage to Australia and New Zealand in 2015 by beating Kenya comprehensively for the second time in succession in Sharjah, sealing their maiden World Cup qualification.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They finished second in the World Cricket League Championship — nine wins in 14 matches — and joined Ireland as the second Associate team in the 2015 World Cup, while the remaining two spots for Associates will be decided by a qualifying tournament in New Zealand in 2014.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan will join Pool A at the World Cup along with Australia, Bangladesh, England, New Zealand, Sri Lanka and another qualifier.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 24 November 2013, Afghanistan beat Kenya to qualify for the 2014 T20 world cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In March 2014, Afghanistan beat Hong Kong in the 2014 ICC World Twenty20 but could not make it to the next stage of super 10 having lost the two matches to Bangladesh and Nepal.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 25 February 2015, Afghanistan won their first Cricket World Cup match, beating Scotland by one wicket.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan participated in the World Twenty20 2016 in India.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They were unable to qualify for the Semi-Finals of the International Tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They defeated the eventual champions, West Indies, during their final group match of the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Their third match was against the full member test team Zimbabwe.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] They played exceptionally well, beating Zimbabwe by 59 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan qualified for the Super 10 stage of the tournament as a result of this match, while Zimbabwe were eliminated.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan progressed to the second phase of a World Twenty20 tournament for the first time.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 25 June 2016, Lalchand Rajput was named as head coach of Afghanistan Cricket Team replacing Pakistan's Inzamam ul Haq with his first outings with the team being a tour of Scotland, Ireland and the Netherlands in July and August of that year.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] He was chosen ahead of Mohammad Yousuf, Herschelle Gibbs and Corey Collymore Rajput is in line for a two-year contract, but that decision would be finalised after the upcoming tour of Europe.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In July 2016, ACB unveiled a strategic plan and set targets for Afghanistan cricket team to be a top-six ODI team by 2019 and a top-three team in both T20Is and ODIs by 2025.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In order to achieve this, ACB created a proposal to be presented to BCCI, to secure annual bilateral matches against India and teams touring India beginning the following year.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Shafiq Stanikzai, Chief Executive of ACB, said the draft had been presented to BCCI president Anurag Thakur in May and further discussions occurred during the ICC Annual Conference in Edinburgh in June 2016.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 25 July 2016, Afghanistan confirmed its first full series against West Indies a top-8 ranked Full member.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Its earlier full series came against a permanent member of ICC was against Zimbabwe.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan toured the Caribbean islands in mid-June 2017 and played 5 ODIs and 3 T20Is.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On the same day, it was announced that Afghanistan would host a full series against Ireland at Greater Noida.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Besides a 4-day intercontinental cup match, Ireland and Afghanistan would play five ODIs and three T20Is in March 2017.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan won the T20I series 3-0 and in the process set a new T20I record of 11 consecutive victories.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] On 22 June 2017, the International Cricket Council (ICC) awarded Afghanistan full Test status, along with Ireland.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In December 2017, the ICC confirmed that Afghanistan were scheduled to play their first Test against India, in late 2018.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] According to the ICC Future Tours Programme for 2019–23, Afghanistan are scheduled to play thirteen Tests.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In January 2018, both the ACB and the BCCI confirmed the Test would be played in June in Bengaluru.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In June 2018, Afghanistan lost their maiden Test match to hosts India by an innings and 262 runs, despite being able to bowl out a strong Indian team in the first innings.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In March 2019 against Ireland, Afghanistan achieved their first Test match victory in their only second Test match, becoming the fourth team after Australia, England and Pakistan to win one of their first two Tests.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In September 2019, Afghanistan beat hosts Bangladesh by 224 runs in a one-off Test tour.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Rain almost resulted in the match being drawn, but finally the weather cleared, allowing the spin-unit of Afghanistan to take the final four wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In August 2021, concerns and doubts were raised over the participation of the Afghanistan national cricket team in the future international matches after the Taliban retook control of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Concerns were raised over the safety of Afghan national cricketers and their families who were still in Afghanistan during the Taliban takeover on 15 August 2021.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] As of 31 August 2021, three of the Afghanistan women's national cricket team had evacuated to Canada, while the others were afraid of how they, as women, would be treated by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The women's team was effectively disbanded.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Taliban spokesmen stated that the Taliban would not disrupt the men's cricket team's participation in international matches and that they would allow Afghanistan to play its first ever bilateral series against Pakistan in Sri Lanka which was scheduled to start in September 2021.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The Pakistan Cricket Board announced in August 2021 that the tour would be rescheduled to 2022.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] This was later moved to 2023 and the tour took place between 24 – 27 March 2023.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Despite the ICC requirement for member countries to organize a women's national team for full membership status, the Afghanistan men's national team is allowed to still compete.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan typically do not play their home matches in Afghanistan due to the ongoing security situation and the lack of international standard facilities.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Afghanistan played their 'home' Intercontinental Cup fixture against Ireland at the Rangiri Dambulla International Stadium in Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Following Afghanistan's World Twenty20 qualifying campaign they played two One Day Internationals against Canada at the Sharjah Cricket Association Stadium in the UAE.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] As plans to resurrect Afghan cricket developed, at least three international standard cricket stadiums have been built in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2016, Shahid Vijay Singh Pathik Sports Complex in Greater Noida became the home ground for the Afghanistan national cricket team after they decided to shift their home ground from Sharjah.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In June 2018, after acquiring test status, Afghanistan changed their home base to Rajiv Gandhi International Cricket Stadium, Dehradun, India.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In May 2019, Afghanistan Cricket Board requested BCCI for a new home stadium.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In August 2019, BCCI approved Ekana Cricket Stadium in Lucknow, India as the new home stadium for the team.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In Test matches, Afghanistan wears cricket whites.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Fielders wear a baggy red cap or red sun hat displaying the ACB logo.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] In limited-overs cricket, Afghanistan wears a predominantly blue kit with splashes of green, red, black, and, occasionally, yellow.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Grey was previously used as the main color between 2012 and 2013.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Fielders wear a blue baseball-style cap or red sun hat.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] For both Test and limited-overs kits, the ACB logo is featured on the left breast, with the main sponsor logo in the center of the shirt.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The secondary sponsor is displayed on the leading sleeve and back of the shirt, with the manufacturer's logo on the non-leading sleeve.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] For ICC tournaments, the main sponsor logo moves to the leading sleeve.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Previously also red, batters' helmets are blue as of late February 2024, with the Afghanistan tricolor flag displayed above the ACB logo.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] The current sponsors are Etisalat and Vany Sports.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] This lists all the players who have played for Afghanistan in the past 12 months or were named in the most recent Test, ODI or T20I squad.
[src:afghanistan-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-cricket-team-p01] Uncapped players are listed in *italics*.
